rants electors to {{abbr|DC|District of Columbia}} as if it were a state, but not more than the least populous state. This has always been three.''\n: ** ''Maine's four electors and Nebraska's five are distributed using the [[#Congressional district method|Congressional district method]].''\n\n== Chronological table ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:80%;line-height:1.1;\"\n|+ <big><big>Number of presidential electors by state and year</big></big>\n|- valign=bottom\n! colspan=2 rowspan=2 style=\"text-align:right\" | Election<br />year\n! colspan=3  | 1788\u20131800\n! colspan=18 | 1804\u20131900\n! colspan=11 | 1904\u20132000\n! colspan=2  | 2004\u2013\n|- valign=bottom\n! [[1788\u201389 United States presidential election|'88]]\n! [[1792 United States presidential election|'92]]\n! [[1796 United States presidential election|'96]]<br />[[1800 United States presidential election|'00]]\n! [[1804 United States presidential election|'04]]<br />[[1808 United States presidential election|'08]]\n! [[1812 United States presidential election|'12]]\n! [[1816 United States presidential election|'16]]\n! [[1820 United States presidential election|'20]]\n! [[1824 United States presidential election|'24]]<br />[[1828 United States presidential election|'28]]\n! [[1832 United States presidential election|'32]]\n! [[1836 United States presidential election|'36]]<br />[[1840 United States presidential election|'40]]\n! [[1844 United States presidential election|'44]]\n! [[1848 United States presidential election|'48]]\n! [[1852 United States presidential election|'52]]<br />[[1856 United States presidential election|'56]]\n! [[1860 United States presidential election|'60]]\n! [[1864 United States presidential election|'64]]<!--\n   NOTE REGARDING SORTING FOR 1864\u201368 ELECTIONS\n   The southern states are shown as an explicit '0' between secession and restoration of representation in Congress.\n   In order to sort these separately from the {{