{"title_page": "Masters of Sex", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name = Masters of Sex\n | image = Masters of Sex title.png\n | image_size = 250px\n | image_alt =\n | genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[historical drama|Period drama]]\n}}\n | developer = [[Michelle Ashford]]\n | caption = \n | based_on = {{Based on|''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''|[[Thomas Maier]]}}\n | starring = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]]\n* [[Teddy Sears]]\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]]\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]]\n}}\n | theme_music_composer = \n | opentheme = \n | endtheme = \n | composer = [[Michael Penn]]\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | num_seasons = 4\n | num_episodes = 46\n | list_episodes = List of Masters of Sex episodes\n | executive_producer = {{Plainlist |\n* Michelle Ashford\n* Sarah Timberman\n* Carl Beverly\n* [[Amy Lippman]]\n* Judith Verno\n}}\n | producer = Michael Sheen<br />Lizzy Caplan <br />Thomas Maier\n | location = {{Plainlist|\n* [[New York City]]\n* [[Los Angeles]]\n}}\n | cinematography = [[Ben Davis (cinematographer)|Ben Davis]]\n | camera = \n | runtime = 55\u201360 minutes\n | company = {{Plainlist|\n* Round Two Productions\n* Timberman/Beverly Productions\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* [[Showtime Networks]]\n}}\n | distributor = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n | channel = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n | picture_format = \n | audio_format = \n | first_aired = {{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|2016|11|13}}\n | preceded_by = \n | followed_by = \n | related = \n | website = \n | website_title = Official website\n | production_website = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of Sex''''' is an American [[period drama]] television series that premiered on September 29, 2013, on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/01/12/showtime-announces-premiere-dates-for-nurse-jackie-dexter-returning-early-ray-donovan-homeland-masters-of-sex-more/165132/|title=Showtime Announces Premiere Dates for 'Nurse Jackie,' 'Dexter' (Returning Early) 'Ray Donovan,' 'Homeland,' 'Masters of Sex' & More|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 12, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> It was developed by [[Michelle Ashford]] and loosely based on [[Thomas Maier]]'s biography ''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''.<ref name=\"lat2013\"/> Set in the 1950s through the late 1960s, the series tells the story of [[Masters and Johnson]] ([[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]] and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]) who are portrayed by [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]]. The series has received critical acclaim. It was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]] in 2013. The series was canceled by Showtime on November 30, 2016, after four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/11/30/masters-of-sex-cancelled-showtime-season-5/ |title=Masters of Sex Is Done at Showtime |publisher=TVLine |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |date=November 30, 2016 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series explores the research and the relationship between [[William Masters]] ([[Michael Sheen]]) and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]] ([[Lizzy Caplan]]), two pioneering researchers of human sexuality at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Maier |first=Thomas |title= Masters Of Sex: The Life and Times of William Masters and Virginia Johnson, The Couple Who Taught America How To Love|year=2009 |publisher= Basic Books |location=New York|isbn=9780465003075|pages=400|asin=B001Y35IZO}}</ref> The series begins in October 1956 and ends in August 1969 with the fourth season.\n\nAs noted by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic, the series \"hangs on bones of fact\"; \"it's more useful for the viewer to think of it as all made up. Because, mostly, it is, and because to the extent it tells the story of two real people, it also adorns the telling with dramatic practicalities, invented characters and narrative detours. Indeed, it's down these side streets, casting a brief light on a passing character (patients, prostitutes, a provost's wife), that the show finds many of its best moments.\"<ref name=\"lat2013\"/>\n\nOther than principal characters, which are partly fictionalized, adults are significantly fictionalized; however, children are entirely fictionalized. In real life, Masters and Johnson each have two children, however, in the series they have three children each. Episodes featuring the children include a disclaimer where it states that their storylines are \"entirely fictitious\". Series creator Michelle Ashford explained, \"We are telling a non-fiction story and one where there are people who are still alive out there, and those people need to be protected. We were advised to add [the baby] to protect the people that are still alive. It wasn't a storytelling prerogative. It had to do with protecting living people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/masters-of-sex-fake-baby/ |title=The Kids Aren't Alright: Behind Masters of Sex's Controversial Children's Stories |website=TV Guide |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n[[File:Cast of Masters of Sex at PaleyFest 2014.jpg|thumb|The cast and crew at [[PaleyFest]] 2014. From left: [[Michelle Ashford]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], Sarah Timberman (executive producer), [[Caitlin FitzGerald]], [[Teddy Sears]] and [[Annaleigh Ashford]]]]\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as [[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]] as Libby Masters\n* [[Teddy Sears]] as Dr. Austin Langham (seasons 1\u20132, recurring seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]] as Dr. Ethan Haas (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]] as Betty Dimello (seasons 2\u20134, recurring season 1)\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Beau Bridges]] as Barton Scully, medical school provost and longtime friend of William Masters\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Margaret Scully, Barton's wife (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Vivian Scully, Barton and Margaret's daughter<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-masters-sex-adds-lovely-419826 |title=Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' Adds 'Lovely Bones' Actress |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Hel\u00e9ne Yorke]] as Jane Martin, a hospital secretary and participant in the sex study\n* Kevin Christy as Lester Linden, the archivist of Masters and Johnson's work\n* [[Julianne Nicholson]] as Dr. Lillian DePaul, a doctor working in the Obstetrics Department of Washington University Hospital (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Ann Dowd]] as Estabrooks 'Essie' Masters, William's mother<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/linda-lavin-to-co-star-in-nbcs-sean-hayes-pilot-ann-dowd-recurs-on-masters-of-sex/ |title=Linda Lavin To Co-Star In NBC\u2019s Sean Hayes Pilot, Ann Dowd Recurs On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=February 4, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Mather Zickel]] as George Johnson, Virginia's ex-husband and father of her children\n* [[Cole Sand]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Noah Robbins]] (season 3) as Henry Johnson, Virginia's son\n* Kayla Madison (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Isabelle Fuhrman]] (seasons 3\u20134) as Tessa Johnson, Virginia's daughter\n* [[Greg Grunberg]] as Gene Moretti, Betty's husband (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Finn Wittrock]] as Dale, a male [[Male prostitution|prostitute]] whom Barton Scully patronizes (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-gay-story/11/2013/ |title=The Compelling Gay Story in \"Masters Of Sex\" |publisher=The Backlot |date=November 19, 2013 |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Betsy Brandt]] as Barbara Sanderson, Masters' new secretary, and later a patient of his clinic (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/breaking-bads-betsy-brandt-joins-689335 |title=Breaking Bad's' Betsy Brandt Joins Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Christian Borle]] as Francis 'Frank' Masters, Jr., the younger brother of William Masters (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/ustv/news/a573109/masters-of-sex-casts-smash-actor-christian-borle.html#~oFzDp7PqIGbiu8 |title=Masters of Sex casts Smash actor Christian Borle |publisher=Digital Spy |first=Tom |last=Eames |date=May 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Keke Palmer]] as Coral, the Masters' African-American nanny (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/keke-palmer-joins-showtimes-masters-of-sex-1201130050/# |title=Keke Palmer Joins Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex' |work=Variety |first=Francesca |last=Bacardi |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Jocko Sims]] as Robert Franklin, Coral's brother and a civil rights activist (season 2)\n* [[Sarah Silverman]] as Helen, Betty's lover (seasons 2\u20134)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/sarah-silverman-masters-of-sex-1201165873/ |title=Sarah Silverman Joins \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 Cast |work=Variety |first=Whitney |last=Friedlander |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Courtney B. Vance]] as Dr. Charles Hendricks, the head of an African-American St. Louis hospital who seeks integration (season 2)<ref name=\"Auberjonois and Vance\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/courtney-b-vance-rene-auberjonois-set-for-season-2-of-masters-of-sex/ |title=Courtney B. Vance & Rene Auberjonois Set For Season 2 Of \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Huston]] as Dr. Douglas Greathouse, the head of a hospital's Obstetrics Department (season 2)\n* [[Artemis Pebdani]] as Flo Packer, the owner of a diet pill company (season 2)\n* [[Adam Arkin]] as Shep Tally, a [[Public relations|PR]] expert hired by Masters and Johnson to help them present their work (season 2)\n* [[Josh Charles]] as Dan Logan (season 3)\n* [[Emily Kinney]] as Nora Everett, a woman fascinated with Bill and Virginia's work who later becomes part of Bill's surrogacy program (season 3)\n* [[Ben Koldyke]] as Paul Edley (season 3)\n* Colin Woodell as Ronald Sturgis (season 3)\n* [[Jaeden Lieberher]] as Johnny Masters, Bill and Libby's son (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Jeremy Strong (actor)|Jeremy Strong]] as Dr. Art Dreesen, a psychologist who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Betty Gilpin]] as Dr. Nancy Leveau, Art's wife and a doctor who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Louise Bell, the head of Alcoholics Anonymous (season 4)\n* [[Kelli O'Hara]] as Dody Oliver, Bill's first love who did not answer his marriage proposal (season 4)\n\n==Development and production==\nShowtime ordered the pilot for ''Masters of Sex'' in August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/08/showtime-picks-up-pilots-from-andrew-gurland-michelle-ashford-ann-biderman/ |title=Showtime Picks Up Pilots From Andrew Gurland, Michelle Ashford & Ann Biderman |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> and greenlit it for series in June 2012, with the first season consisting of twelve episodes.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2012/tv/news/showtime-gives-series-orders-to-donovan-sex-1118055335/ |title=Showtime gives series orders to 'Donovan,' 'Sex' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=June 11, 2012 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWriter/producer [[Michelle Ashford]] serves as [[showrunner]] for ''Masters of Sex''. She assembled a majority-female writing staff, although she says this was unintentional.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2013/09/dirty-talk-with-the-woman-behind-masters-of-sex.html |title=Q&A: Dirty Talk With the Woman Behind ''Masters of Sex'' |work=New York Magazine |first=Allison P. |last=Davis |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAshford created the character of Barton Scully out of a combination of several men whom Masters knew. One of them was gay, but was not the man serving as provost during Masters' initial study.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-creator-on-the-shows-gay-storyline/11/2013/ |title=\"Masters Of Sex\" Creator On The Show\u2019s \"Exciting\" Gay Storyline |publisher=The Backlot |first=Jim |last=Halterman |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProp master Jeffrey Johnson noted the difficulty of obtaining accurate information about [[sex toy|sexual devices]] from the time period. \"They were so taboo it was hard to find research drawings. People didn\u2019t even put them in writing.\" He obtained some vintage vibrators and [[dildo]]s for use in the series along with acquiring [[condom]]s manufactured in the era (which did not have the reservoir tips of modern condoms). He designed \"Ulysses\", a transparent dildo with attached camera first seen in the pilot episode, from scratch, along with a diaphragm sizing kit seen in later episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/09/masters-of-sex-prop-master-glass-dildos.html |title=Talking to ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s Prop Master About Glass Dildos and Old Condoms |work=Vulture |first=Molly |last=Langmuir |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Annaleigh Ashford]], who has a recurring role in the first season as Betty Dimello, was promoted to series regular in season two.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/12/annaleigh-ashford-regular-on-masters-of-sex-departs-kinky-boots/ |title=Annaleigh Ashford Upped To Regular On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019, Will Depart \u2018Kinky Boots\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[opening credits]] sequence was created by design studio Elastic. The sequence, which includes suggestive, tongue-in-cheek sex metaphors and symbols, received a mixed response from critics; it placed on both best and worst lists for opening credit sequences. It was also nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Design]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/2980158/masters-of-sex-season-2-premier-opening-credits/ |title=Behind the Unusual Opening Credits to Masters of Sex |work=Time |first=Feeney |last=Nolan |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Series overview ==\n{{Main|List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n{{:List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#BDD6D3;\"|\n| 1\n| 90% (58 reviews)\n| 86 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B30027;\"|\n| 2\n| 98% (43 reviews)\n| 89 (17 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0D3952;\"|\n| 3\n| 69% (32 reviews)\n| 72 (15 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A7BA9A;\"|\n| 4\n| 80% (10 reviews)\n| 70 (5 reviews)\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first season of ''Masters of Sex'' received critical acclaim. Based on 58 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season received a 90% approval rating from critics, with a rating average of 8.26 out of 10. The site's consensus states: \"Seductive and nuanced, ''Masters of Sex'' features smart performances, deft direction, and impeccable period decor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s01/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 1 (2013) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the first season a score of 86 out of 100, based on 32 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-1 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] listed it as one of the top ten television series of 2013.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2013/film/awards/afi-names-best-movies-and-tv-shows-of-2013-1200937298/ | title=AFI Names Best Movies and TV Shows of 2013 | work=Variety |date=December 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 9, 2013 | first=Tim |last=Gray}}</ref>\n\nMatt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote that \"There is no more fascinating, or entertaining, new series this fall season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Weekend-Playlist-Masters-1071377.aspx |title=Weekend Playlist: ''Masters of Sex'' and ''Homeland'', ''Breaking Bad'' Finale on Jam-Packed Sunday |work=TV Guide |first=Matt |last=Roush |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Diane Werts of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave it an \"A\" grade, complimenting the series on its use of humor, stating \"its deft balance of epic scope and whimsical humanity\", as well as the strong performances of the actors and creator [[Michelle Ashford]]'s \"scene-setting scripts\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/masters-of-sex-review-showtime-scores-1.6139803 |title='Masters of Sex' review: Showtime scores |work=Newsday |first=Diane |last=Werts |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' particularly praised the performances, calling them \"extraordinary\" and \"stunning\", and noting the series' A-list directors, among them [[Michael Apted]] and [[John Madden (director)|John Madden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Masters-of-Sex-review-Satisfying-look-at-sex-4847308.php |title='Masters of Sex' review: Satisfying look at sex |work=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegand |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that after the first two episodes, \"the characters get better and more complex, the story builds, strange things start to happen and now I can't wait to see how its interweaving plots unfold.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/showtimes-masters-of-sex-starts-off-slow-and-deliberate-and-then-finds-the-right-spot/2013/09/26/19a08e06-263d-11e3-b3e9-d97fb087acd6_story.html |title=Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 gets better as it goes along |work=The Washington Post |first=Hank |last=Stuever |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Alan Sepinwall of [[HitFix]] praised lead actors [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]], calling them \"terrific\", and saying that \"''Masters of Sex'' is the best new show of the fall by a very long stretch. It's also a refreshing anomaly: a prestige cable drama that doesn't feel like a recombination of elements from 15 shows that came before it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-michael-sheen-lizzy-caplan-shine-in-showtimes-masters-of-sex |title=Review: Michael Sheen & Lizzy Caplan shine in Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |publisher=HitFix |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate= November 7, 2013}}</ref>  According to Robert Lloyd, the ''Los Angeles Times'' television critic, the show is a \"handsome thing, another well-dressed romp through the American mid-century, when things (we imagine) were simpler and (so we like to think) less sophisticated, but also more exciting. And it's true that sexual naivet\u00e9 of that age can seem incredible in a day when pornography is just another thing on your platform of choice. But even in an age when ''Masters of Sex'' is a TV show, the subject remains stubbornly powerful, private and confounding. We have come far, and we are still cavemen.<ref name=\"lat2013\">{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/28/entertainment/la-et-st-masters-of-sex-review |title=Review: 'Masters of Sex' explores the science of sex |date=September 28, 2013 |first=Robert |last=Lloyd |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim equal to if not greater than the first season. It received a score of 89 out of 100 on Metacritic based on 17 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-2 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 2 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 98% approval rating among critics based on 43 reviews, with a rating average of 8.52 out of 10. The consensus reads: \"Boasting an expanded storyline and broader focus, ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s second season improves on its already outstanding predecessor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s02/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 2|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received generally positive reviews from critics, although received more mixed reviews than the previous seasons. It has a Metacritic score of 72 out of 100 based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-3 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 3 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 69% approval rating among critics based on 32 reviews, with a rating average of 7.61 out of 10. The consensus reads, \"With a six-year leap forward in the timeline, ''Masters of Sex'' takes an intriguing dramatic turn, but may leave a few viewers feeling frustrated.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s03/|title=Masters of Sex: Season 3|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received generally positive reviews from critics. It has a Metacritic score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-4 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 4 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Masters of Sex}}\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn June 2013, the series was honored, along with five others, with the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Most Exciting New Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/television-awards/the-btja-announces-icon-award-recipient-and-most-exciting-new-series-honorees/ |title=The BTJA Announces Icon Award Recipient and Most Exciting New Series Honorees |publisher=The Broadcast Television Journalists Association |date=June 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> The series received two nominations for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s, for Best New Series and Best Episodic Drama for \"Pilot\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>  For the [[71st Golden Globe Awards]], the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]], and [[Michael Sheen]] was nominated [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Drama Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/12/golden-globe-nominations-2014-globes-awards-nominees/ |title=Golden Globes: ''House of Cards'', ''The Good Wife'', ''Candelabra'' and ''Breaking Bad'' Lead Noms; ''Parks & Rec'', ''Brooklyn'', Spader and Maslany Score Nods |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=December 12, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], [[Lizzy Caplan]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], [[Beau Bridges]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]], and [[Allison Janney]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/08/16/emmys-2014-creative-arts-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2014: ''Scandal'', ''OITNB'' and ''Masters of Sex'' Stars, ''True Detective'', ''Bob's Burgers'' Among Early Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 16, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\nIn Canada, the series debuted on September 29, 2013, on [[The Movie Network]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |title=Masters of Sex |publisher=The Movie Network |accessdate=September 28, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132110/http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Australia, the series premiered on [[SBS One]] on October 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Picks: It's a Date, Masters of Sex and Upper Middle Bogan|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/tv-picks-it8217s-a-date-masters-of-sex-and-upper-middle-bogan/story-e6frfmyi-1226732378805|publisher=News.com.au|first=Dianne|last=Butler|date=October 3, 2013|accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> In Ireland, the series premiered on October 4, 2013, on [[RT\u00c92|RT\u00c9 Two]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/tv-highlight/Masters-of-Sex/217603.htm |title=Masters of Sex RTE2: 11.20pm|publisher=entertainment.ie|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> In the UK, it debuted on [[Channel 4]] on October 8, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/09/channel-4-sets-uk-premiere-date-for-masters-of-sex/ |title=Channel 4 Sets UK Premiere Date For \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In New Zealand, it debuted on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]] on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/blogs/on-the-box/9320727/Masters-Of-Sex-masters-sex-on-TV |title=Masters Of Sex masters sex on TV|publisher=Stuff.co.nz |first=Chris |last=Philpott|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Virgin Media]] acquired the UK rights for ''Masters of Sex'' and it started airing on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/09/virgin-media-to-launch-dedicated-4k-channel-picks-up-uk-rights-to-shut-eye-masters-of-sex-more/ |title=Virgin Media To Launch Dedicated 4K Channel; Picks Up UK Rights To \u2018Shut Eye\u2019, \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 & More |website=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|2137109}}\n* {{tv.com show|masters-of-sex}}\n\n{{Masters of Sex}}\n{{Showtime Network programming}}\n\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American medical television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Showtime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Erotic television series]]\n[[Category:Erotic drama television series]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n | show_name = Masters of Sex\n | image = Masters of Sex title.png\n | image_size = 250px\n | image_alt =\n | genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[historical drama|Period drama]]\n}}\n | developer = [[Michelle Ashford]]\n | caption = \n | based_on = {{Based on|''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''|[[Thomas Maier]]}}\n | starring = {{Plainlist |\n* [[Michael Sheen]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]]\n* [[Teddy Sears]]\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]]\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]]\n}}\n | theme_music_composer = \n | opentheme = \n | endtheme = \n | composer = [[Michael Penn]]\n | country = United States\n | language = English\n | num_seasons = 4\n | num_episodes = 46\n | list_episodes = List of Masters of Sex episodes\n | executive_producer = {{Plainlist |\n* Michelle Ashford\n* Sarah Timberman\n* Carl Beverly\n* [[Amy Lippman]]\n* Judith Verno\n}}\n | producer = Michael Sheen<br />Lizzy Caplan <br />Thomas Maier\n | location = {{Plainlist|\n* [[New York City]]\n* [[Los Angeles]]\n}}\n | cinematography = [[Ben Davis (cinematographer)|Ben Davis]]\n | camera = \n | runtime = 55\u201360 minutes\n | company = {{Plainlist|\n* Round Two Productions\n* Timberman/Beverly Productions\n* [[Sony Pictures Television]]\n* [[Showtime Networks]]\n}}\n | distributor = [[CBS Television Distribution]]\n | channel = [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]]\n | picture_format = \n | audio_format = \n | first_aired = {{Start date|2013|9|29}}\n | last_aired = {{End date|2016|11|13}}\n | preceded_by = \n | followed_by = \n | related = \n | website = \n | website_title = Official website\n | production_website = \n}}\n\n'''''Masters of Sex''''' is an American [[period drama]] television series that premiered on September 29, 2013, on [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]].<ref name=\"premiere\">{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2013/01/12/showtime-announces-premiere-dates-for-nurse-jackie-dexter-returning-early-ray-donovan-homeland-masters-of-sex-more/165132/|title=Showtime Announces Premiere Dates for 'Nurse Jackie,' 'Dexter' (Returning Early) 'Ray Donovan,' 'Homeland,' 'Masters of Sex' & More|last=Seidman|first=Robert|work=TV by the Numbers|date=January 12, 2013|accessdate=January 12, 2013}}</ref> It was developed by [[Michelle Ashford]] and loosely based on [[Thomas Maier]]'s biography ''[[Masters of Sex (book)|Masters of Sex]]''.<ref name=\"lat2013\"/> Set in the 1950s through the late 1960s, the series tells the story of [[Masters and Johnson]] ([[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]] and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]) who are portrayed by [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]]. The series has received critical acclaim. It was nominated for a [[Golden Globe Award]] for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]] in 2013. The series was canceled by Showtime on November 30, 2016, after four seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2016/11/30/masters-of-sex-cancelled-showtime-season-5/ |title=Masters of Sex Is Done at Showtime |publisher=TVLine |first=Vlada |last=Gelman |date=November 30, 2016 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\nThe series explores the research and the relationship between [[William Masters]] ([[Michael Sheen]]) and [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]] ([[Lizzy Caplan]]), two pioneering researchers of human sexuality at [[Washington University in St. Louis|Washington University]] in [[St. Louis, Missouri]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Maier |first=Thomas |title= Masters Of Sex: The Life and Times of William Masters and Virginia Johnson, The Couple Who Taught America How To Love|year=2009 |publisher= Basic Books |location=New York|isbn=9780465003075|pages=400|asin=B001Y35IZO}}</ref> The series begins in October 1956 and ends in August 1969 with the fourth season.\n\nAs noted by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' television critic, the series \"hangs on bones of fact\"; \"it's more useful for the viewer to think of it as all made up. Because, mostly, it is, and because to the extent it tells the story of two real people, it also adorns the telling with dramatic practicalities, invented characters and narrative detours. Indeed, it's down these side streets, casting a brief light on a passing character (patients, prostitutes, a provost's wife), that the show finds many of its best moments.\"<ref name=\"lat2013\"/>\n\nOther than principal characters, which are partly fictionalized, adults are significantly fictionalized; however, children are entirely fictionalized. In real life, Masters and Johnson each have two children, however, in the series they have three children each. Episodes featuring the children include a disclaimer where it states that their storylines are \"entirely fictitious\". Series creator Michelle Ashford explained, \"We are telling a non-fiction story and one where there are people who are still alive out there, and those people need to be protected. We were advised to add [the baby] to protect the people that are still alive. It wasn't a storytelling prerogative. It had to do with protecting living people.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/news/masters-of-sex-fake-baby/ |title=The Kids Aren't Alright: Behind Masters of Sex's Controversial Children's Stories |website=TV Guide |first=Hanh |last=Nguyen |date=August 11, 2015 |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n[[File:Cast of Masters of Sex at PaleyFest 2014.jpg|thumb|The cast and crew at [[PaleyFest]] 2014. From left: [[Michelle Ashford]], [[Michael Sheen]], [[Lizzy Caplan]], Sarah Timberman (executive producer), [[Caitlin FitzGerald]], [[Teddy Sears]] and [[Annaleigh Ashford]]]]\n\n===Main cast===\n* [[Michael Sheen]] as [[William Masters|Dr. William Masters]]\n* [[Lizzy Caplan]] as [[Virginia E. Johnson|Virginia Johnson]]\n* [[Caitlin FitzGerald]] as Libby Masters\n* [[Teddy Sears]] as Dr. Austin Langham (seasons 1\u20132, recurring seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Nicholas D'Agosto]] as Dr. Ethan Haas (season 1, guest season 2)\n* [[Annaleigh Ashford]] as Betty Dimello (seasons 2\u20134, recurring season 1)\n\n===Recurring cast===\n* [[Beau Bridges]] as Barton Scully, medical school provost and longtime friend of William Masters\n* [[Allison Janney]] as Margaret Scully, Barton's wife (seasons 1\u20133)\n* [[Rose McIver]] as Vivian Scully, Barton and Margaret's daughter<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/showtimes-masters-sex-adds-lovely-419826 |title=Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' Adds 'Lovely Bones' Actress |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=February 8, 2013 |accessdate=February 11, 2013 |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Hel\u00e9ne Yorke]] as Jane Martin, a hospital secretary and participant in the sex study\n* Kevin Christy as Lester Linden, the archivist of Masters and Johnson's work\n* [[Julianne Nicholson]] as Dr. Lillian DePaul, a doctor working in the Obstetrics Department of Washington University Hospital (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Ann Dowd]] as Estabrooks 'Essie' Masters, William's mother<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/02/linda-lavin-to-co-star-in-nbcs-sean-hayes-pilot-ann-dowd-recurs-on-masters-of-sex/ |title=Linda Lavin To Co-Star In NBC\u2019s Sean Hayes Pilot, Ann Dowd Recurs On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=February 4, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Mather Zickel]] as George Johnson, Virginia's ex-husband and father of her children\n* [[Cole Sand]] (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Noah Robbins]] (season 3) as Henry Johnson, Virginia's son\n* Kayla Madison (seasons 1\u20132) and [[Isabelle Fuhrman]] (seasons 3\u20134) as Tessa Johnson, Virginia's daughter\n* [[Greg Grunberg]] as Gene Moretti, Betty's husband (seasons 1\u20132)\n* [[Finn Wittrock]] as Dale, a male [[Male prostitution|prostitute]] whom Barton Scully patronizes (season 1)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-gay-story/11/2013/ |title=The Compelling Gay Story in \"Masters Of Sex\" |publisher=The Backlot |date=November 19, 2013 |accessdate=November 19, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Betsy Brandt]] as Barbara Sanderson, Masters' new secretary, and later a patient of his clinic (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/breaking-bads-betsy-brandt-joins-689335 |title=Breaking Bad's' Betsy Brandt Joins Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |first=Lesley |last=Goldberg |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Christian Borle]] as Francis 'Frank' Masters, Jr., the younger brother of William Masters (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/ustv/news/a573109/masters-of-sex-casts-smash-actor-christian-borle.html#~oFzDp7PqIGbiu8 |title=Masters of Sex casts Smash actor Christian Borle |publisher=Digital Spy |first=Tom |last=Eames |date=May 23, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Keke Palmer]] as Coral, the Masters' African-American nanny (season 2)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/keke-palmer-joins-showtimes-masters-of-sex-1201130050/# |title=Keke Palmer Joins Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex' |work=Variety |first=Francesca |last=Bacardi |date=March 12, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Jocko Sims]] as Robert Franklin, Coral's brother and a civil rights activist (season 2)\n* [[Sarah Silverman]] as Helen, Betty's lover (seasons 2\u20134)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/sarah-silverman-masters-of-sex-1201165873/ |title=Sarah Silverman Joins \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 Cast |work=Variety |first=Whitney |last=Friedlander |date=April 28, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Courtney B. Vance]] as Dr. Charles Hendricks, the head of an African-American St. Louis hospital who seeks integration (season 2)<ref name=\"Auberjonois and Vance\">{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2014/05/courtney-b-vance-rene-auberjonois-set-for-season-2-of-masters-of-sex/ |title=Courtney B. Vance & Rene Auberjonois Set For Season 2 Of \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Erik |last=Pedersen |date=May 19, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Danny Huston]] as Dr. Douglas Greathouse, the head of a hospital's Obstetrics Department (season 2)\n* [[Artemis Pebdani]] as Flo Packer, the owner of a diet pill company (season 2)\n* [[Adam Arkin]] as Shep Tally, a [[Public relations|PR]] expert hired by Masters and Johnson to help them present their work (season 2)\n* [[Josh Charles]] as Dan Logan (season 3)\n* [[Emily Kinney]] as Nora Everett, a woman fascinated with Bill and Virginia's work who later becomes part of Bill's surrogacy program (season 3)\n* [[Ben Koldyke]] as Paul Edley (season 3)\n* Colin Woodell as Ronald Sturgis (season 3)\n* [[Jaeden Lieberher]] as Johnny Masters, Bill and Libby's son (seasons 3\u20134)\n* [[Jeremy Strong (actor)|Jeremy Strong]] as Dr. Art Dreesen, a psychologist who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Betty Gilpin]] as Dr. Nancy Leveau, Art's wife and a doctor who is brought in to help lessen Bill and Virginia's workload (season 4)\n* [[Niecy Nash]] as Louise Bell, the head of Alcoholics Anonymous (season 4)\n* [[Kelli O'Hara]] as Dody Oliver, Bill's first love who did not answer his marriage proposal (season 4)\n\n\n==Development and production==\nShowtime ordered the pilot for ''Masters of Sex'' in August 2011,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2011/08/showtime-picks-up-pilots-from-andrew-gurland-michelle-ashford-ann-biderman/ |title=Showtime Picks Up Pilots From Andrew Gurland, Michelle Ashford & Ann Biderman |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=August 21, 2011 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref> and greenlit it for series in June 2012, with the first season consisting of twelve episodes.<ref name=\"variety\">{{cite news |url=https://variety.com/2012/tv/news/showtime-gives-series-orders-to-donovan-sex-1118055335/ |title=Showtime gives series orders to 'Donovan,' 'Sex' |last=Littleton |first=Cynthia |date=June 11, 2012 |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=July 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nWriter/producer [[Michelle Ashford]] serves as [[showrunner]] for ''Masters of Sex''. She assembled a majority-female writing staff, although she says this was unintentional.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nymag.com/thecut/2013/09/dirty-talk-with-the-woman-behind-masters-of-sex.html |title=Q&A: Dirty Talk With the Woman Behind ''Masters of Sex'' |work=New York Magazine |first=Allison P. |last=Davis |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAshford created the character of Barton Scully out of a combination of several men whom Masters knew. One of them was gay, but was not the man serving as provost during Masters' initial study.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thebacklot.com/masters-of-sex-creator-on-the-shows-gay-storyline/11/2013/ |title=\"Masters Of Sex\" Creator On The Show\u2019s \"Exciting\" Gay Storyline |publisher=The Backlot |first=Jim |last=Halterman |date=November 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\nProp master Jeffrey Johnson noted the difficulty of obtaining accurate information about [[sex toy|sexual devices]] from the time period. \"They were so taboo it was hard to find research drawings. People didn\u2019t even put them in writing.\" He obtained some vintage vibrators and [[dildo]]s for use in the series along with acquiring [[condom]]s manufactured in the era (which did not have the reservoir tips of modern condoms). He designed \"Ulysses\", a transparent dildo with attached camera first seen in the pilot episode, from scratch, along with a diaphragm sizing kit seen in later episodes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vulture.com/2013/09/masters-of-sex-prop-master-glass-dildos.html |title=Talking to ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s Prop Master About Glass Dildos and Old Condoms |work=Vulture |first=Molly |last=Langmuir |date=September 30, 2013 |accessdate=September 30, 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[Annaleigh Ashford]], who has a recurring role in the first season as Betty Dimello, was promoted to series regular in season two.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.deadline.com/2013/12/annaleigh-ashford-regular-on-masters-of-sex-departs-kinky-boots/ |title=Annaleigh Ashford Upped To Regular On \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019, Will Depart \u2018Kinky Boots\u2019 |publisher=Deadline.com |first=Nellie |last=Andreeva |date=December 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 8, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe [[opening credits]] sequence was created by design studio Elastic. The sequence, which includes suggestive, tongue-in-cheek sex metaphors and symbols, received a mixed response from critics; it placed on both best and worst lists for opening credit sequences. It was also nominated for the [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Main Title Design]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://time.com/2980158/masters-of-sex-season-2-premier-opening-credits/ |title=Behind the Unusual Opening Credits to Masters of Sex |work=Time |first=Feeney |last=Nolan |date=July 14, 2014 |accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Series overview ==\n{{Main|List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n{{:List of Masters of Sex episodes}}\n\n==Reception==\n\n===Critical response===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"float: right;text-align:center; width:%70;margin:10px\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" colspan=\"2\" | Critical response\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Rotten Tomatoes]]\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | [[Metacritic]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#BDD6D3;\"|\n| 1\n| 90% (58 reviews)\n| 86 (32 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#B30027;\"|\n| 2\n| 98% (43 reviews)\n| 89 (17 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#0D3952;\"|\n| 3\n| 69% (32 reviews)\n| 72 (15 reviews)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"width:12px; background:#A7BA9A;\"|\n| 4\n| 80% (10 reviews)\n| 70 (5 reviews)\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first season of ''Masters of Sex'' received critical acclaim. Based on 58 reviews collected by [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the first season received a 90% approval rating from critics, with a rating average of 8.26 out of 10. The site's consensus states: \"Seductive and nuanced, ''Masters of Sex'' features smart performances, deft direction, and impeccable period decor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url =https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s01/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 1 (2013) |publisher=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> [[Metacritic]] gave the first season a score of 86 out of 100, based on 32 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-1 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 1 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The [[American Film Institute]] listed it as one of the top ten television series of 2013.<ref name=\"afi\">{{cite web | url=https://variety.com/2013/film/awards/afi-names-best-movies-and-tv-shows-of-2013-1200937298/ | title=AFI Names Best Movies and TV Shows of 2013 | work=Variety |date=December 9, 2013 |accessdate=December 9, 2013 | first=Tim |last=Gray}}</ref>\n\nMatt Roush of ''[[TV Guide]]'' wrote that \"There is no more fascinating, or entertaining, new series this fall season.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/News/Weekend-Playlist-Masters-1071377.aspx |title=Weekend Playlist: ''Masters of Sex'' and ''Homeland'', ''Breaking Bad'' Finale on Jam-Packed Sunday |work=TV Guide |first=Matt |last=Roush |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Diane Werts of ''[[Newsday]]'' gave it an \"A\" grade, complimenting the series on its use of humor, stating \"its deft balance of epic scope and whimsical humanity\", as well as the strong performances of the actors and creator [[Michelle Ashford]]'s \"scene-setting scripts\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsday.com/entertainment/tv/masters-of-sex-review-showtime-scores-1.6139803 |title='Masters of Sex' review: Showtime scores |work=Newsday |first=Diane |last=Werts |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[David Wiegand]] of the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' particularly praised the performances, calling them \"extraordinary\" and \"stunning\", and noting the series' A-list directors, among them [[Michael Apted]] and [[John Madden (director)|John Madden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sfgate.com/tv/article/Masters-of-Sex-review-Satisfying-look-at-sex-4847308.php |title='Masters of Sex' review: Satisfying look at sex |work=San Francisco Chronicle |first=David |last=Wiegand |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Hank Stuever of ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that after the first two episodes, \"the characters get better and more complex, the story builds, strange things start to happen and now I can't wait to see how its interweaving plots unfold.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/entertainment/tv/showtimes-masters-of-sex-starts-off-slow-and-deliberate-and-then-finds-the-right-spot/2013/09/26/19a08e06-263d-11e3-b3e9-d97fb087acd6_story.html |title=Showtime\u2019s \u2018Masters of Sex\u2019 gets better as it goes along |work=The Washington Post |first=Hank |last=Stuever |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> Alan Sepinwall of [[HitFix]] praised lead actors [[Michael Sheen]] and [[Lizzy Caplan]], calling them \"terrific\", and saying that \"''Masters of Sex'' is the best new show of the fall by a very long stretch. It's also a refreshing anomaly: a prestige cable drama that doesn't feel like a recombination of elements from 15 shows that came before it.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hitfix.com/whats-alan-watching/review-michael-sheen-lizzy-caplan-shine-in-showtimes-masters-of-sex |title=Review: Michael Sheen & Lizzy Caplan shine in Showtime's 'Masters of Sex' |publisher=HitFix |first=Alan |last=Sepinwall |date=September 26, 2013 |accessdate= November 7, 2013}}</ref>  According to Robert Lloyd, the ''Los Angeles Times'' television critic, the show is a \"handsome thing, another well-dressed romp through the American mid-century, when things (we imagine) were simpler and (so we like to think) less sophisticated, but also more exciting. And it's true that sexual naivet\u00e9 of that age can seem incredible in a day when pornography is just another thing on your platform of choice. But even in an age when ''Masters of Sex'' is a TV show, the subject remains stubbornly powerful, private and confounding. We have come far, and we are still cavemen.<ref name=\"lat2013\">{{cite web |url=https://articles.latimes.com/2013/sep/28/entertainment/la-et-st-masters-of-sex-review |title=Review: 'Masters of Sex' explores the science of sex |date=September 28, 2013 |first=Robert |last=Lloyd |work=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=December 1, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe second season also received critical acclaim equal to if not greater than the first season. It received a score of 89 out of 100 on Metacritic based on 17 reviews, indicating \"universal acclaim\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-2 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 2 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2014}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 98% approval rating among critics based on 43 reviews, with a rating average of 8.52 out of 10. The consensus reads: \"Boasting an expanded storyline and broader focus, ''Masters of Sex''{{'}}s second season improves on its already outstanding predecessor.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s02/ |title=Masters of Sex: Season 2|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe third season received generally positive reviews from critics, although received more mixed reviews than the previous seasons. It has a Metacritic score of 72 out of 100 based on 15 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-3 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 3 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=July 12, 2015}}</ref> On Rotten Tomatoes, it has a 69% approval rating among critics based on 32 reviews, with a rating average of 7.61 out of 10. The consensus reads, \"With a six-year leap forward in the timeline, ''Masters of Sex'' takes an intriguing dramatic turn, but may leave a few viewers feeling frustrated.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/masters-of-sex/s03/|title=Masters of Sex: Season 3|publisher=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=July 14, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe fourth season received generally positive reviews from critics. It has a Metacritic score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 reviews.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/masters-of-sex/season-4 |title=Masters of Sex \u2013 Season 4 Reviews |publisher=Metacritic |accessdate=September 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and nominations===\n{{main|List of awards and nominations received by Masters of Sex}}\n{{Anchor|Awards|Accolades}}\nIn June 2013, the series was honored, along with five others, with the [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Most Exciting New Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.criticschoice.com/television-awards/the-btja-announces-icon-award-recipient-and-most-exciting-new-series-honorees/ |title=The BTJA Announces Icon Award Recipient and Most Exciting New Series Honorees |publisher=The Broadcast Television Journalists Association |date=June 10, 2013 |accessdate=June 29, 2013}}</ref> The series received two nominations for the 2014 [[Writers Guild of America Award]]s, for Best New Series and Best Episodic Drama for \"Pilot\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/05/writers-guild-award-nominations-2014-list-wga/ |title=''Breaking Bad'', ''Orange Is the New Black'', ''House of Cards'' Lead 2014 WGA Nominations |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=December 5, 2013 |accessdate=December 5, 2013}}</ref>  For the [[71st Golden Globe Awards]], the series was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Television Series \u2013 Drama|Best Drama Series]], and [[Michael Sheen]] was nominated [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actor \u2013 Television Series Drama|Best Drama Actor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2013/12/12/golden-globe-nominations-2014-globes-awards-nominees/ |title=Golden Globes: ''House of Cards'', ''The Good Wife'', ''Candelabra'' and ''Breaking Bad'' Lead Noms; ''Parks & Rec'', ''Brooklyn'', Spader and Maslany Score Nods |publisher=TVLine |first=Matt Webb |last=Mitovich |date=December 12, 2013 |accessdate=December 12, 2013}}</ref> For the [[66th Primetime Emmy Awards]], [[Lizzy Caplan]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series]], [[Beau Bridges]] received a nomination for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actor in a Drama Series]], and [[Allison Janney]] won for [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series|Outstanding Guest Actress in a Drama Series]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2014/tv/news/emmy-nominations-2014-list-emmys-nominees-1201260236/ |title=2014 Emmy Awards: \u2018Game of Thrones,\u2019 \u2018Fargo\u2019 Lead Nominations |work=Variety |first=Brian |last=Lowry |date=July 10, 2014 |accessdate=July 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://tvline.com/2014/08/16/emmys-2014-creative-arts-winners-list/ |title=Emmys 2014: ''Scandal'', ''OITNB'' and ''Masters of Sex'' Stars, ''True Detective'', ''Bob's Burgers'' Among Early Winners |publisher=TVLine |first=Michael |last=Ausiello |date=August 16, 2014 |accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==International broadcast==\nIn Canada, the series debuted on September 29, 2013, on [[The Movie Network]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |title=Masters of Sex |publisher=The Movie Network |accessdate=September 28, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002132110/http://www.themovienetwork.ca/series/mastersofsex/ |archive-date=October 2, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In Australia, the series premiered on [[SBS One]] on October 3, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=TV Picks: It's a Date, Masters of Sex and Upper Middle Bogan|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/television/tv-picks-it8217s-a-date-masters-of-sex-and-upper-middle-bogan/story-e6frfmyi-1226732378805|publisher=News.com.au|first=Dianne|last=Butler|date=October 3, 2013|accessdate=October 7, 2013}}</ref> In Ireland, the series premiered on October 4, 2013, on [[RT\u00c92|RT\u00c9 Two]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://entertainment.ie/tv-highlight/Masters-of-Sex/217603.htm |title=Masters of Sex RTE2: 11.20pm|publisher=entertainment.ie|accessdate=October 10, 2013}}</ref> In the UK, it debuted on [[Channel 4]] on October 8, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tvwise.co.uk/2013/09/channel-4-sets-uk-premiere-date-for-masters-of-sex/ |title=Channel 4 Sets UK Premiere Date For \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 |publisher=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 25, 2013 |accessdate=September 29, 2013}}</ref> In New Zealand, it debuted on [[SoHo (TV channel)|SoHo]] on October 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/blogs/on-the-box/9320727/Masters-Of-Sex-masters-sex-on-TV |title=Masters Of Sex masters sex on TV|publisher=Stuff.co.nz |first=Chris |last=Philpott|date=October 24, 2013|accessdate=November 7, 2013}}</ref> [[Virgin Media]] acquired the UK rights for ''Masters of Sex'' and it started airing on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tvwise.co.uk/2018/09/virgin-media-to-launch-dedicated-4k-channel-picks-up-uk-rights-to-shut-eye-masters-of-sex-more/ |title=Virgin Media To Launch Dedicated 4K Channel; Picks Up UK Rights To \u2018Shut Eye\u2019, \u2018Masters Of Sex\u2019 & More |website=TVWise |first=Patrick |last=Munn |date=September 12, 2018 |accessdate=October 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* {{IMDb title|2137109}}\n* {{tv.com show|masters-of-sex}}\n\n{{Masters of Sex}}\n{{Showtime Network programming}}\n\n[[Category:2013 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2016 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:2010s American LGBT-related drama television series]]\n[[Category:2010s American medical television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Lesbian-related television programs]]\n[[Category:Television series about dysfunctional families]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1950s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1960s]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1970s]]\n[[Category:Showtime (TV network) original programming]]\n[[Category:Television series by CBS Television Studios]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:Erotic television series]]\n[[Category:Erotic drama television series]]\n", "name_user": "Drovethrughosts", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRecurring cast", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masters_of_Sex"}
{"title_page": "International Legal Foundation", "text_new": "The '''International Legal Foundation (ILF)''' is an [[international non-governmental organization]] founded in 2001. It is focused on establishing and strengthening criminal legal aid systems around the world. In addition to its technical assistance work with foreign governments, the ILF provides direct legal aid services through its multiple in-country offices. To date, ILF lawyers have defended more than 60,000 accused individuals worldwide. \n\n== Founding ==\nWhile serving as an observer to the [[Rwandan genocide|Rwandan genocide trials]], attorney Natalie Rea noticed there were \u201ca handful\u201d defense lawyers available<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soundslikeportraits.com/natalie-rea-lawyer|title=Sounds Like Portraits: Natalie Rea, criminal defense lawyer: 'I basically don't trust authority\"|website=soundslikeportraits.com}}</ref> to represent the over 70,000 incarcerated at Kigali Central Prison. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5NdtfmzesHc|title=RWANDA: REPORT FROM KIGALI CENTRAL PRISON, AP Archive}}</ref> She returned home to the [[United States]] and founded Legal Aid Rwanda <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dev2019.oakfnd.org/international-human-rights-heroes-natalie-rea/|title=International Human Rights Heroes: NATALIE REA|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>, which recruited lawyers to travel to [[Rwanda]] and provide pretrial defense. In 2001, Rea founded the International Legal Foundation. Rea created the ILF to address legal aid crises in foreign countries, and expand criminal defense services for the indigent. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.court-access.org/our-team-2|title=Our Board|website=The Court-Access Project}}</ref> She served as its Executive Director until 2012, when she was succeeded by current director Jennifer Smith. According to its website, Rea now serves as a Senior Advisor on its Board of Directors. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/natalie-rae|title=Natalie Rea|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n== Programs and Work Abroad ==\nThe majority of ILF programs and staff are located outside of the United States, primarily in its program countries. The ILF has six primary areas of focus: legal aid access; pretrial justice reform; gender equality; racial, ethnic and religious minorities; children and youth; and the [[Sustainable Development Goals|UN SDG16+ framework]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/areas-of-focus|title=Areas of Focus|website=The ILF}}</ref>\nThe ILF hires lawyers local to each country of operation and trains them in legal aid best practices. ILF staff members work with governments globally, sharing their expertise to promote criminal justice reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/partners/the-international-legal-foundation/|title=The International Legal Foundation|website=Global Citizen}}</ref> Coordination of all programs is carried out from its US Headquarters, which are located in [[New York City]]. <ref>[https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4193728 Guidestar Profile]</ref> Its year-round international fellowship program stations experienced defense lawyers from around the world in program countries, to train ILF lawyers in criminal defense and provide additional support to the legal aid office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/international-fellowships|title=Become a Fellow|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n=== Country Offices ===\nILF programs are currently active in [[Afghanistan]], [[Myanmar]], [[Nepal]], [[Tunisia]], and the [[West Bank]]. \n\nThe ILF was first established in Afghanistan in 2003, and has expanded its practice to 22 provinces. According to its website, it has provided legal aid services on more than 56,000 cases in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/afghanistan|title=Afghanistan|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published an article about ILF client Brishna, who was accused of murdering her son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-male-dominated-afghanistan-justice-for-women-is-complicated/2019/06/22/e9cf1884-91f5-11e9-956a-88c291ab5c38_story.html|title=In male-dominated Afghanistan, justice for women is complicated|website=Washington Post}}</ref> In that same year, the ILF launched a partnership with [[Ministry of Justice (Afghanistan)|Afghanistan\u2019s Ministry of Justice]] (MoJ) to expand the reach of legal aid and accelerate progress in achieving [[Sustainable Development Goal 16|UN Sustainable Development Goal 16]], justice for all. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/partnership/?p=35414,|title=Strengthening Afghanistan's Legal Aid System, #SDGAction35414}}</ref> Also in 2019, the ILF won the first annual Rule of Law Competition <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ili.org/about/news/1066-announcement-of-winners-of-urola%E2%80%99s-first-annual-rule-of-law-competition.html?fbclid=IwAR29MOhFYpWaMMvx71e1mL8Oqo8E0wTeb7ZEvei-QyCyg-QIu_O5Y5RhVzM|title=Announcement of Winners of UROLA\u2019s First Annual Rule of Law Competition|website=www.ili.org}}</ref>, hosted by the United Rule of Law Appeal (UROLA), for its work in Afghanistan.\n\nThe ILF started operating in Myanmar in 2017, where it is active in five regions and staff have worked on more than 300 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/myanmar|title=Myanmar|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, it partnered with [[UNICEF|UNICEF Myanmar]] to support the implementation of the Child Rights Law, connecting young people with juvenile defense lawyers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/myanmar/press-releases/international-legal-foundation-and-unicef-myanmar-join-forces-protect-children|title=The International Legal Foundation and UNICEF Myanmar join forces to protect children in conflict with the law|website=www.unicef.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in Nepal in 2008, where it has worked on an estimated 7,500 cases across five districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/nepal|title=Nepal|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2018, the Nepal program became locally-led, and was independently registered as the Public Defender Society of Nepal (PDS-Nepal).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pdsnepal.org/content/who-we-are|title=Public Defender Society: Mission and Story|website=pdsnepal.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in the West Bank in 2010, opening its first office in [[Ramallah]].<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/west-bank|title=West Bank|website=The ILF}}</ref> According to its website, staff have worked on more than 4,000 cases across 11 governorates.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\" />\n\nThe ILF began its program in Tunisia in 2015.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/tunisia|title=Tunisia|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Tunis]] office took on its 500th case.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\" />\n\n=== United Nations ===\nThe ILF works alongside [[List of specialized agencies of the United Nations|United Nations agencies]] in a number of ways. The ILF actively participates in the [[United Nations Congress on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice|UN Commission on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, 28th Session. \"CCPCJ 2019 Programme\". Page 10.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, Twenty-fifth Session. \"CCPCJ Programme 2016\". Page 4.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, TWENTY-SECOND SESSION. \"Side_Events_Programme_22_CCPCJ_2013\". Page 4.}}</ref>, and retains consultative status with the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/civilsociety/consultativeStatusSummary.do?profileCode=615040|title=United Nations Civil Society Participation (iCSO) \u2013 Login|website=esango.un.org}}</ref>\n\n=== International Legal Aid Conference ===\nIn 2014, the ILF co-founded the biennial International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems (ILAC) with the Open Society Justice Initiative (OSJI), the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP), and the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\">{{Cite web|url=http://ilac2018.ge/|title=ILAC - Homepage|website=ilac2018.ge}}</ref> The conference highlights \u201cglobal efforts to implement the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, which provide that States should put in place a comprehensive legal aid system.\u201d <ref name=\"About the ILAC\" />\nILAC has been held in the following locations: [[Johannesburg]], South Africa (2014),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/2014_Johannesburg_Declaration_on_Implementation_of_UNPGLA.pdf|title=The Johannesburg Declaration on the Implementation of the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems}}</ref> [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina  (2016),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/justice-and-prison-reform/LegalAid/E_CN15_2017_CRP2_e_V1703525.pdf|title=Outcome of the Second International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, held in Buenos Aires, Argentina, 15-17 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Tbilisi]], Georgia (2018).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\" /> The 4th ILAC is scheduled to be held in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil in September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ilac2020.rj.def.br/|title=ILAC 2020 - 4\u00ba International Conference on Access to Legal Aid Criminal Justice Systems|website=ilac2020.rj.def.br}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.theilf.org International Legal Foundation Official Website]\n\n[[Category:International nongovernmental organizations]]\n", "text_old": "The '''International Legal Foundation (ILF)''' is an [[international non-governmental organization]] founded in 2001. It is focused on establishing and strengthening criminal legal aid systems around the world. In addition to its technical assistance work with foreign governments, the ILF provides direct legal aid services through its multiple in-country offices. To date, ILF lawyers have defended more than 60,000 accused individuals worldwide. \n\n== Founding ==\nWhile serving as an observer to the [[Rwandan genocide|Rwandan genocide trials]], attorney Natalie Rea noticed there were \u201ca handful\u201d defense lawyers available<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://soundslikeportraits.com/natalie-rea-lawyer|title=Sounds Like Portraits: Natalie Rea, criminal defense lawyer: 'I basically don't trust authority\"|website=soundslikeportraits.com}}</ref> to represent the over 70,000 incarcerated at Kigali Central Prison. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5NdtfmzesHc|title=RWANDA: REPORT FROM KIGALI CENTRAL PRISON, AP Archive}}</ref> She returned home to the [[United States]] and founded Legal Aid Rwanda <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dev2019.oakfnd.org/international-human-rights-heroes-natalie-rea/|title=International Human Rights Heroes: NATALIE REA|date=June 20, 2016}}</ref>, which recruited lawyers to travel to [[Rwanda]] and provide pretrial defense. In 2001, Rea founded the International Legal Foundation. Rea created the ILF to address legal aid crises in foreign countries, and expand criminal defense services for the indigent. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.court-access.org/our-team-2|title=Our Board|website=The Court-Access Project}}</ref> She served as its Executive Director until 2012, when she was succeeded by current director Jennifer Smith. According to its website, Rea now serves as a Senior Advisor on its Board of Directors. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/natalie-rae|title=Natalie Rea|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n== Programs and Work Abroad ==\nThe majority of ILF programs and staff are located outside of the United States, primarily in its program countries. The ILF has six primary areas of focus: legal aid access; pretrial justice reform; gender equality; racial, ethnic and religious minorities; children and youth; and the [[Sustainable Development Goals|UN SDG16+ framework]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/areas-of-focus|title=Areas of Focus|website=The ILF}}</ref>\nThe ILF hires lawyers local to each country of operation and trains them in legal aid best practices. ILF staff members work with governments globally, sharing their expertise to promote criminal justice reform.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.globalcitizen.org/en/partners/the-international-legal-foundation/|title=The International Legal Foundation|website=Global Citizen}}</ref> Coordination of all programs is carried out from its US Headquarters, which are located in [[New York City]]. <ref>[https://www.guidestar.org/profile/13-4193728 Guidestar Profile]</ref> Its year-round international fellowship program stations experienced defense lawyers from around the world in program countries, to train ILF lawyers in criminal defense and provide additional support to the legal aid office.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/international-fellowships|title=Become a Fellow|website=The ILF}}</ref>\n\n=== Country Offices ===\nILF programs are currently active in [[Afghanistan]], [[Myanmar]], [[Nepal]], [[Tunisia]], and the [[West Bank]]. \n\nThe ILF was first established in Afghanistan in 2003, and has expanded its practice to 22 provinces. According to its website, it has provided legal aid services on more than 56,000 cases in the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/afghanistan|title=Afghanistan|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' published an article about ILF client Brishna, who was accused of murdering her son.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/in-male-dominated-afghanistan-justice-for-women-is-complicated/2019/06/22/e9cf1884-91f5-11e9-956a-88c291ab5c38_story.html|title=In male-dominated Afghanistan, justice for women is complicated|website=Washington Post}}</ref> In that same year, the ILF launched a partnership with [[Ministry of Justice (Afghanistan)|Afghanistan\u2019s Ministry of Justice]] (MoJ) to expand the reach of legal aid and accelerate progress in achieving [[Sustainable Development Goal 16|UN Sustainable Development Goal 16]], justice for all. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/partnership/?p=35414,|title=Strengthening Afghanistan's Legal Aid System, #SDGAction35414}}</ref> Also in 2019, the ILF won the first annual Rule of Law Competition <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ili.org/about/news/1066-announcement-of-winners-of-urola%E2%80%99s-first-annual-rule-of-law-competition.html?fbclid=IwAR29MOhFYpWaMMvx71e1mL8Oqo8E0wTeb7ZEvei-QyCyg-QIu_O5Y5RhVzM|title=Announcement of Winners of UROLA\u2019s First Annual Rule of Law Competition|website=www.ili.org}}</ref>, hosted by the United Rule of Law Appeal (UROLA), for its work in Afghanistan.\n\nThe ILF started operating in Myanmar in 2017, where it is active in five regions and staff have worked on more than 300 cases.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/myanmar|title=Myanmar|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2019, it partnered with [[UNICEF|UNICEF Myanmar]] to support the implementation of the Child Rights Law, connecting young people with juvenile defense lawyers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unicef.org/myanmar/press-releases/international-legal-foundation-and-unicef-myanmar-join-forces-protect-children|title=The International Legal Foundation and UNICEF Myanmar join forces to protect children in conflict with the law|website=www.unicef.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in Nepal in 2008, where it has worked on an estimated 7,500 cases across five districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/nepal|title=Nepal|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2018, the Nepal program became locally-led, and was independently registered as the Public Defender Society of Nepal (PDS-Nepal).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pdsnepal.org/content/who-we-are|title=Public Defender Society: Mission and Story|website=pdsnepal.org}}</ref>\n\nThe ILF began work in the West Bank in 2010, opening its first office in [[Ramallah]].<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/west-bank|title=West Bank|website=The ILF}}</ref> According to its website, staff have worked on more than 4,000 cases across 11 governorates.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, West Bank\" />\n\nThe ILF began its program in Tunisia in 2015.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.theilf.org/tunisia|title=Tunisia|website=The ILF}}</ref> In 2020, the [[Tunis]] office took on its 500th case.<ref name=\"International Legal Foundation, Tunisia\" />\n\n=== United Nations ===\nThe ILF works alongside [[List of specialized agencies of the United Nations|United Nations agencies]] in a number of ways. The ILF actively participates in the [[United Nations Congress on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice|UN Commission on Crime Prevention and Criminal Justice]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, 28th Session. \"CCPCJ 2019 Programme\". Page 10.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, Twenty-fifth Session. \"CCPCJ Programme 2016\". Page 4.}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/commissions/CCPCJ/19-02848_CCPCJ_2019_Programme_ebook_NEW.pdf|title=UNITED NATIONS COMMISSION ON CRIME PREVENTION AND CRIMINAL JUSTICE, TWENTY-SECOND SESSION. \"Side_Events_Programme_22_CCPCJ_2013\". Page 4.}}</ref>, and retains consultative status with the [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://esango.un.org/civilsociety/consultativeStatusSummary.do?profileCode=615040|title=United Nations Civil Society Participation (iCSO) \u2013 Login|website=esango.un.org}}</ref>\n\n=== International Legal Aid Conference ===\nIn 2014, the ILF co-founded the biennial International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems (ILAC) with the Open Society Justice Initiative (OSJI), the [[United Nations Development Programme]] (UNDP), and the [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] (UNODC).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\">{{Cite web|url=http://ilac2018.ge/|title=ILAC - Homepage|website=ilac2018.ge}}</ref> The conference highlights \u201cglobal efforts to implement the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, which provide that States should put in place a comprehensive legal aid system.\u201d <ref name=\"About the ILAC\" />\nILAC has been held in the following locations: [[Johannesburg]], South Africa (2014),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/pdf/criminal_justice/2014_Johannesburg_Declaration_on_Implementation_of_UNPGLA.pdf|title=The Johannesburg Declaration on the Implementation of the United Nations Principles and Guidelines on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems}}</ref> [[Buenos Aires]], Argentina  (2016),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.unodc.org/documents/justice-and-prison-reform/LegalAid/E_CN15_2017_CRP2_e_V1703525.pdf|title=Outcome of the Second International Conference on Access to Legal Aid in Criminal Justice Systems, held in Buenos Aires, Argentina, 15-17 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Tbilisi]], Georgia (2018).<ref name=\"About the ILAC\" /> The 4th ILAC is scheduled to be held in [[Rio de Janeiro]], Brazil in September 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ilac2020.rj.def.br/|title=ILAC 2020 - 4\u00ba International Conference on Access to Legal Aid Criminal Justice Systems|website=ilac2020.rj.def.br}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External Links ==\n[http://www.theilf.org International Legal Foundation Official Website]\n\n[[Category:International nongovernmental organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Sagotreespirit", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor cleanup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Legal_Foundation"}
{"title_page": "Tabrez Ansari lynching", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Tabrez Ansari lynching\n| image      =\n| caption    =\n|map= {{Location map|India\n|width = 250\n|float = right\n|label =\n  |marksize = 8\n  | lat_deg = 22.8027\n  | lon_deg = 86.1807\n  }}\n| map_caption = Dhatkidih, Jamshedpur\n| location   = Dhatkidih, [[Jharkhand]], India\n| coordinates =\n| target     = Tabrez Ansari\n| date       = 17 June 2019\n| time       =\n| timezone   =\n| type       = Lynching\n| fatalities = 1 (Tabrez Ansari)\n| perps      = Mob\n| susperps   =\n| weapons    = Blunt objects\n}}\n\nOn 17 June 2019, 24-year-old '''Tabrez Ansari''' was attacked by a [[Mob lynching|lynch mob]] in [[Jharkhand]], India. He was tied to a tree, brutally beaten on suspicion of bike  theft;<ref name=\"video report\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/india/tabrez-assault-clip-showing-chant-not-doctored/cid/1704037|title=Tabrez assault clip showing chant \u2018not doctored\u2019|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> Ansari, a Muslim, was also forced to chant Hindu sayings. He died several days later, succumbing to the injuries. The incident came to light after a video of the lynching went viral.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=Jai Shri Ram: The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=10 July 2019 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> India's Prime Minister commented on this lynching in the [[Parliament of India]].\n\n==Events==\nTabrez Ansari was an orphan.\n\nOn the morning of 18 June, the police were notified. Ansari was arrested and locked up in Saraykela Police Station.<ref name=bbc1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/hindi/india-48758990|title=\u0924\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u0905\u0902\u0938\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u094b \u0917\u093e\u0901\u0935 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0938\u094b\u0928\u0942 \u0925\u0947, \u092e\u093e\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094c\u0928?|first=\u0906\u0928\u0902\u0926|last=\u0926\u0924\u094d\u0924|date=25 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> His wife received a call from him telling her what had happened. She informed her relatives.\n\nHis uncle visited the station and saw that he was severely injured. He asked the police to provide medical treatment, but Ansari was sent to prison without it. Two days later. when his uncle went to see him in prison, Ansari was not in any condition to talk. He tried to reach the medical officer of the prison too, but was unable to meet him. On the morning of 22 June, Ansari's family received news that his condition was severe, and he was admitted to Sadar Hospital. His relatives reached the hospital by 7:30 am, but by that time, he died.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n==Response==\nThe Tabrez family demanded that the perpetrators be tried under Section 302 (Punishment for murder) of the Indian Penal Code.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jharkhand-lynching-family-of-man-beaten-on-suspicion-of-theft-demands-compensation-job-for-wife-2764534 |title=Jharkhand lynching: Family of man beaten on suspicion of theft demands compensation, job for wife |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Ansari's wife said that her husband was mercilessly beaten. She demanded justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442|title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended|last=Kumar|first=Manish|date=2019-06-05|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June, 11 arrests were made, and two policemen were suspended for \"not reporting the seriousness of the issue to the higher authorities\" and \"{{sic|register}} a case of lynching on the very same day\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442?amp=1&akamai-rum=off |title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended |date=25 June 2019 |author=Manish Kumar |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref>\n\nAn SIT team was assigned to investigate the case. The Saraikela-Kharsawan district police charged 11 of the 13 named accused in the case on 29 July. The murder charges were then dropped, but later reinstated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Police restore murder charge against 11 accused |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-police-restore-murder-charge-against-11-accused-1600603-2019-09-18 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA medical panel of five members was formed to look into the death. The resulting medical report concluded that Tabrez Ansari suffered a skull fracture caused by a \"hard and blunt object\", a [[subarachnoid haemorrhage]], and clotting of blood in the lower layer of the skull; and suggests that these injuries led to the [[cardiac arrest]] that resulted in Ansari's death. The consumption of poison was ruled out.<ref name=\"India Today Medical Report\">{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: New medical report suggests cardiac arrest was due to skull fracture, other injuries |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-medical-report-cardiac-arrest-skull-fracture-jharkhand-police-1598668-2019-09-13 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2019, the police dropped the murder charges by giving cardiac arrest as the reason of death, which led to an uproar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/murder-charge-dropped-in-tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-in-jharkhand-2303797.html|title=Murder Charge Dropped in Tabrez Ansari Lynching Case in Jharkhand|website=News18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-police-drop-murder-charges-against-11-citing-autopsy-report-1597490-2019-09-10|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: Police drop murder charges against 11 citing autopsy report|author=India Today Web Desk New (Input from Satyajeet Kumar)|date= 10 September 2019 |website=India Today}}</ref> Due to this, the police were accused of weakening the case. On 18 September 2019, the police filed a supplementary chargesheet after obtaining the opinion of a board of doctors of [[MGM Medical College and Hospital]], reinstating the murder charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-murder-charge-back-on-all-accused/article29452797.ece |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case accused face murder charge |date=18 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\nThe lynching resulted in public anger,<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\">{{cite news |title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man beaten to death |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/protests-indian-cities-muslim-man-beaten-death-190627005534986.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> debates on the use of \"Jai Shri Ram\" as an attack slogan<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|last=Pandey|first=Geeta|date=10 July 2019|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and multiple protests, including one in [[New Delhi]] held near the parliament house, where protesters chanted slogans against the [[BJP]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and demanded an end to anti-Muslim violence.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\nModi commented on the lynching in parliament, that he was pained<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-protests-lynching-idINKCN1TR2AW|title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man is lynched, Modi says he is 'pained'|last=Siddiqui|first=Zeba|date=26 June 2019|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> to hear about the incident and calling for \"the strictest possible punishment to the accused\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Rahul Gandhi]], at the time President of the [[Indian National Congress]], called the lynching a \"blot on humanity\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] called the lynching \"a conspiracy of secularists\",<ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news |title=VHP brands Tabrez Ansari lynching as conspiracy |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/vhp-brands-tabrez-ansari-lynching-conspiracy-mob-lynching-case-1598037-2019-09-11 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> which VHP Joint General Secretary Surendra Jain blamed on \"the Khan Market Mafia, which has repeatedly been maligning Hindu society, India and humanity.\"<ref name=\"India Today\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Violence in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl6MZG1bcOs Newsreport including filming of lynching] on [[NDTV]], 24 June 2019\n\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=March 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title      = Tabrez Ansari lynching\n| image      =\n| caption    =\n|map= {{Location map|India\n|width = 250\n|float = right\n|label =\n  |marksize = 8\n  | lat_deg = 22.8027\n  | lon_deg = 86.1807\n  }}\n| map_caption = Dhatkidih, Jamshedpur\n| location   = Dhatkidih, [[Jharkhand]], India\n| coordinates =\n| target     = Tabrez Ansari\n| date       = 17 June 2019\n| time       =\n| timezone   =\n| type       = Lynching\n| fatalities = 1 (Tabrez Ansari)\n| perps      = Mob\n| susperps   =\n| weapons    = Blunt objects\n}}\n\nOn 17 June 2019, 24-year-old '''Tabrez Ansari''' was attacked by a [[Mob lynching|lynch mob]] in [[Jharkhand]], India. He was tied to a tree, brutally beaten on suspicion of bike  theft;<ref name=\"video report\">{{Cite web|url=https://m.telegraphindia.com/india/tabrez-assault-clip-showing-chant-not-doctored/cid/1704037|title=Tabrez assault clip showing chant \u2018not doctored\u2019|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref> Ansari, a Muslim, was also forced to chant Hindu sayings. He died several days later, succumbing to the injuries. The incident came to light after a video of the lynching went viral.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053 |title=Jai Shri Ram: The Hindu chant that became a murder cry |date=10 July 2019 |publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> India's Prime Minister commented on this lynching in the [[Parliament of India]].\n\n==Events==\nTabrez Ansari was an orphan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/opinion/columns/no-one-killed-tabrez-ansari-lynching-jharkhand-police-5993644/|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Why the outcome must concern us all|date=14 September 2019}}</ref> He lived in [[Pune]] and worked there for seven years.<ref name=\"auto\"/> He visited his hometown of Kadamdih occasionally on festivals. For [[Eid al-Fitr]] he visited Kadamdih.<ref name=\"auto\"/> During the visit, on 17 June, he went to [[Jamshedpur]] with two friends on the bike of one of his friends.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsclick.in/Jharkhand-Lynching-Tabrez-Ansari-Religious-Polarisation|title=After Tabrez Ansari\u2019s Lynching, Attempts at Religious Polarisation Continue in Jharkhand Village|date=28 June 2019|website=NewsClick}}</ref> While returning from Jamshedpur, he was caught in the village Dhatkidih, near Kadamdih. He was tied to a tree by the mob and brutally beaten on the suspicion of bike theft. While mob was beating him, a video was made by an unidentified person in the mob. He was forced to say religious slogans such as \"[[Jai Shri Ram]]\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/25/world/asia/india-hindu-muslim-beating.html|title=Forced to Chant Hindu Slogans, Muslim Man Is Beaten to Death in India|last=Raj|first=Suhasini|date=2019-06-25|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-04|last2=Nordland|first2=Rod|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and \"Jai [[Hanuman]]\", which translates from Hindi to \"hail Lord Ram\" or \"victory to Lord Ram\".<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/lynch-mob-to-victim-chant-jai-shri-ram-and-jai-hanuman-suggests-footage/cid/1693066|title=Lynch mob to victim: Chant \u2018Jai Shri Ram\u2019 and 'Jai Hanuman'|website=www.telegraphindia.com}}</ref>\n\nOn the morning of 18 June, the police were notified. Ansari was arrested and locked up in Saraykela Police Station.<ref name=bbc1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/hindi/india-48758990|title=\u0924\u092c\u0930\u0947\u091c\u093c \u0905\u0902\u0938\u093e\u0930\u0940 \u0924\u094b \u0917\u093e\u0901\u0935 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u0947 \u0932\u093f\u090f \u0938\u094b\u0928\u0942 \u0925\u0947, \u092e\u093e\u0930\u0928\u0947 \u0935\u093e\u0932\u0947 \u0915\u094c\u0928?|first=\u0906\u0928\u0902\u0926|last=\u0926\u0924\u094d\u0924|date=25 June 2019|via=www.bbc.com}}</ref> His wife received a call from him telling her what had happened. She informed her relatives.\n\nHis uncle visited the station and saw that he was severely injured. He asked the police to provide medical treatment, but Ansari was sent to prison without it. Two days later. when his uncle went to see him in prison, Ansari was not in any condition to talk. His uncle again contacted the police for medical help, but he was denied. He tried to reach the medical officer of the prison too, but was unable to meet him. On the morning of 22 June, Ansari's family received news that his condition was severe, and he was admitted to Sadar Hospital. His relatives reached the hospital by 7:30 am, but by that time, he died.<ref name=bbc1/>\n\n==Response==\nThe Tabrez family demanded that the perpetrators be tried under Section 302 (Punishment for murder) of the Indian Penal Code.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-jharkhand-lynching-family-of-man-beaten-on-suspicion-of-theft-demands-compensation-job-for-wife-2764534 |title=Jharkhand lynching: Family of man beaten on suspicion of theft demands compensation, job for wife |date=24 June 2019 |newspaper=[[Daily News and Analysis]]}}</ref> Ansari's wife said that her husband was mercilessly beaten because he was a Muslim. She demanded justice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442|title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended|last=Kumar|first=Manish|date=2019-06-05|website=NDTV.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|accessdate=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 June, 11 arrests were made, and two policemen were suspended for \"not reporting the seriousness of the issue to the higher authorities\" and \"{{sic|register}} a case of lynching on the very same day\"<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/jharkhand-mob-killing-five-arrested-so-far-two-cops-suspended-for-negligence-2058442?amp=1&akamai-rum=off |title=Jharkhand Mob Killing: 11 Men Arrested, 2 Police Officers Suspended |date=25 June 2019 |author=Manish Kumar |newspaper=Daily News and Analysis}}</ref>\n\nAn SIT team was assigned to investigate the case. The Saraikela-Kharsawan district police charged 11 of the 13 named accused in the case on 29 July. The murder charges were then dropped, but later reinstated.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case: Police restore murder charge against 11 accused |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-police-restore-murder-charge-against-11-accused-1600603-2019-09-18 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA medical panel of five members was formed to look into the death. The resulting medical report concluded that Tabrez Ansari suffered a skull fracture caused by a \"hard and blunt object\", a [[subarachnoid haemorrhage]], and clotting of blood in the lower layer of the skull; and suggests that these injuries led to the [[cardiac arrest]] that resulted in Ansari's death. The consumption of poison was ruled out.<ref name=\"India Today Medical Report\">{{cite news |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: New medical report suggests cardiac arrest was due to skull fracture, other injuries |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-medical-report-cardiac-arrest-skull-fracture-jharkhand-police-1598668-2019-09-13 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 September 2019, the police dropped the murder charges by giving cardiac arrest as the reason of death, which led to an uproar.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/murder-charge-dropped-in-tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-in-jharkhand-2303797.html|title=Murder Charge Dropped in Tabrez Ansari Lynching Case in Jharkhand|website=News18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tabrez-ansari-lynching-police-drop-murder-charges-against-11-citing-autopsy-report-1597490-2019-09-10|title=Tabrez Ansari lynching: Police drop murder charges against 11 citing autopsy report|author=India Today Web Desk New (Input from Satyajeet Kumar)|date= 10 September 2019 |website=India Today}}</ref> Due to this, the police were accused of weakening the case. On 18 September 2019, the police filed a supplementary chargesheet after obtaining the opinion of a board of doctors of [[MGM Medical College and Hospital]], reinstating the murder charges.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/other-states/tabrez-ansari-lynching-case-murder-charge-back-on-all-accused/article29452797.ece |title=Tabrez Ansari lynching case accused face murder charge |date=18 September 2019 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]]}}</ref>\n\nThe lynching resulted in public anger,<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\">{{cite news |title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man beaten to death |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/06/protests-indian-cities-muslim-man-beaten-death-190627005534986.html |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=www.aljazeera.com}}</ref> debates on the use of \"Jai Shri Ram\" as an attack slogan<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-48882053|title=The Hindu chant that became a murder cry|last=Pandey|first=Geeta|date=10 July 2019|work=[[BBC]]|accessdate=20 November 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and multiple protests, including one in [[New Delhi]] held near the parliament house, where protesters chanted slogans against the [[BJP]] and Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] and demanded an end to anti-Muslim violence.<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\nModi commented on the lynching in parliament, that he was pained<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/india-protests-lynching-idINKCN1TR2AW|title=Protests in Indian cities after Muslim man is lynched, Modi says he is 'pained'|last=Siddiqui|first=Zeba|date=26 June 2019|website=[[Reuters]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-04}}</ref> to hear about the incident and calling for \"the strictest possible punishment to the accused\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Rahul Gandhi]], at the time President of the [[Indian National Congress]], called the lynching a \"blot on humanity\".<ref name=\"Al Jazeera\"/>\n\n[[Vishwa Hindu Parishad]] called the lynching \"a conspiracy of secularists\",<ref name=\"India Today\">{{cite news |title=VHP brands Tabrez Ansari lynching as conspiracy |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/vhp-brands-tabrez-ansari-lynching-conspiracy-mob-lynching-case-1598037-2019-09-11 |accessdate=20 November 2019 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> which VHP Joint General Secretary Surendra Jain blamed on \"the Khan Market Mafia, which has repeatedly been maligning Hindu society, India and humanity.\"<ref name=\"India Today\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Violence against Muslims in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Cl6MZG1bcOs Newsreport including filming of lynching] on [[NDTV]], 24 June 2019\n\n[[Category:Lynching deaths in India]]\n[[Category:Anti-Muslim violence in India]]\n[[Category:Riots and civil disorder in India]]\n", "name_user": "165.225.76.234", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tabrez_Ansari_lynching"}
